    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-11-06T22:19:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-11-06T22:19:00-05:00" n="771"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d771">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.95B/11–650: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Austin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to <gloss type="to">the Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-11-06T22:19:00-05:00"
                            >November 6, 1950—10:19 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 6—11:29 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>788. Chauvel (France) thinks it is important that as soon as possible UC or
                        <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss> issue a statement of assurance
                    that the UNC will not damage or destroy hydro-electric facilities on the Yalu
                    River nor interfere with normal power uses of these facilities. Chauvel believes
                    such an assurance would “simplify and clarify” the issues presented by Chinese
                    Communist intervention in Korea.</p>
                <p>Independently Bebler made same suggestion. Also Officer (Australia)<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d771fn1">Sir Keith Officer, Australian Representative to the U.N.
                        General Assembly.</note> made similar suggestion, adding further suggestion
                    that we might indicate that a neutral “cordon sanitaire” could be set up along
                    the frontier perhaps on a 20-mile strip. This indication would be subject to
                    present need for cleaning out hostile military elements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
